{"summary_of_the_paper":"This paper introduces Synthetic Environments (SEs) and Reward Networks (RNs) as learned neural proxies for reinforcement learning environments and reward functions. SEs jointly model state dynamics and rewards, and are optimized via a bi-level scheme: inner-loop RL agent training on the proxy, outer-loop evolution strategies update proxy parameters to maximize agent performance in the real environment. RNs learn reward modifiers only. The authors demonstrate that once an SE is learned, new agents can be trained entirely on the proxy with fewer real-environment interactions, retaining performance. Experiments on CartPole, Acrobot, CliffWalking, MountainCarContinuous, and HalfCheetah show speedups, hyperparameter robustness, and transfer to unseen agents. A qualitative analysis suggests SEs and RNs bias agents toward relevant states via compressed representations.","main_review":"Strengths: The paper presents a novel, agent-agnostic framework to learn environment and reward proxies via a clean bi-level optimization, leveraging evolution strategies for broad algorithm compatibility. The empirical evaluation is thorough across five classic tasks, multiple RL algorithms, and analyses of hyperparameter sensitivity, transfer to unseen agents, and qualitative behavior. The code release supports reproducibility.

Weaknesses: The environments studied are relatively simple and fully observable; it remains unclear how SEs scale to high-dimensional or partially observed tasks (e.g., vision-based, continuous control at scale). The computational cost of ES with dozens of workers may limit applicability. Comparison to standard model-based RL (e.g., supervised dynamics models or meta-gradients) is limited—an explicit MBRL baseline would strengthen claims. The RN variants introduce many hyperparameters; guidance for selection and stability in sparse or noisy settings is underexplored. The utility of SEs for safety-critical or non-stationary environments is not addressed. Finally, more ablations on ES design choices and potential overfitting would clarify robustness.

Questions and suggestions: How do SEs perform on pixel-level domains or tasks with image inputs? Can the authors provide wall-clock cost per SE/RN training to contextualize resource requirements? Have the authors tried meta-gradient outer loops rather than ES? A direct comparison to a supervised dynamics model trained on the same data would illustrate the benefit of the bi-level agent-aware loss. A deeper study on partial observability, data efficiency during SE learning, and potential biases introduced by the learned proxies would improve clarity.","summary_of_the_review":"This paper proposes learning neural proxies for RL environments and rewards using bi-level optimization with evolution strategies, demonstrating efficiency and transfer benefits on classic benchmarks. While the idea is novel and well evaluated, concerns remain about scalability to higher-dimensional tasks, resource costs, and comparisons to standard model-based RL.","recommendation":"6: marginally above the acceptance threshold."}

{"summary_of_the_paper":"This paper introduces Synthetic Environments (SEs) and Reward Networks (RNs), neural‐network proxies for full environment dynamics and reward shaping, respectively, to accelerate and generalize reinforcement learning (RL). SEs learn both next‐state transitions and rewards via a bi‐level optimization: an inner loop trains an arbitrary RL agent on the SE, while an outer loop uses evolution strategies (ES) on real‐environment performance to evolve the SE parameters. RNs learn to augment or replace reward signals under a similar meta‐learning scheme. The authors evaluate SEs on classic control tasks CartPole and Acrobot and RNs on four domains—including Cliff Walking, MountainCarContinuous, and HalfCheetah—demonstrating that SEs can train new agents without further real‐environment interaction and that both SEs and RNs accelerate agent learning, are robust to hyperparameter variation, and transfer to unseen agents. Qualitative analyses suggest that learned proxies bias agents toward relevant state‐reward representations.","main_review":"Strengths: The paper proposes a novel, agent-agnostic meta-learning framework for learning synthetic environments and reward functions that directly optimize downstream RL performance. The bi-level ES approach avoids unstable meta-gradients and is compatible with a wide range of inner-loop RL algorithms. Experiments on multiple tasks and agents, including transfer to unseen algorithms, provide convincing evidence that SEs and RNs can accelerate learning by 30–65% while maintaining task performance. The authors provide qualitative analyses of state and reward distributions and open-source their code and models, supporting reproducibility.

Weaknesses: The SE case is limited to low-dimensional control tasks; attempts to scale SEs to higher-dimensional or partially observable domains (e.g., Humanoid) failed under modest ES budgets. The approach requires many real-environment interactions to learn SEs, offsetting its benefits for expensive simulators or robotics. Comparisons to supervised model-based baselines (e.g., PETS, World Models) or curriculum generators are limited, and key ablations (e.g., impact of ES hyperparameters, score transformations) are deferred to the appendix. The computational cost of bi-level ES and sensitivity to population size and noise scales poorly. RNs show occasional policy collapse late in training and rely on task-specific early stopping. Partial observability, long‐horizon tasks, and safety constraints are not addressed.

Suggestions: Evaluate SEs on a mid‐scale continuous task (e.g., half‐Cheetah dynamics) with larger ES budgets or compare against state-of-the-art model-based RL to quantify trade-offs. Ablate ES parameters, score transforms, and inner-loop episode budgets to assess robustness. Include resource‐cost vs. sample‐efficiency analyses and discuss how to reduce real-environment interactions during SE learning. Study partially observable or procedurally generated domains to demonstrate generality.","summary_of_the_review":"The paper presents an innovative agent-agnostic meta-learning method for synthetic environments and reward networks that accelerates RL on toy benchmarks and transfers across agents. While experiments and analyses are thorough and code is provided, the approach is limited to low-dimensional tasks, is computationally expensive to scale, and lacks comparisons to model‐based RL baselines. Additional ablations, scalability studies, and mid-scale benchmarks are needed to establish practical significance.","recommendation":"6: marginally above the acceptance threshold."}

{"summary_of_the_paper":"This paper introduces the notions of Synthetic Environments (SEs) and Reward Networks (RNs) as neural network–based proxy models for reinforcement learning (RL) environments. Using a bi‐level optimization scheme with Evolution Strategies in the outer loop and standard RL algorithms in the inner loop, the authors train SEs to capture both state dynamics and rewards, and RNs to learn reward shaping functions. They demonstrate on classic control tasks (CartPole, Acrobot, Cliff Walking, MountainCar, HalfCheetah) that agents trained solely on learned SEs or augmented by RNs can match or exceed real‐environment performance, achieve substantial sample efficiency gains, and transfer to unseen agents. Code, models, and hyperparameter settings are released for reproducibility.","main_review":"Strengths: 1) The concept of learning entire synthetic MDPs and separate reward proxies via a purely performance‐driven bi‐level optimization is novel and well motivated. 2) The approach is agent‐agnostic, compatible with value‐based and actor‐critic methods, and demonstrates robust gains in sample efficiency. 3) Empirical evaluation covers multiple environments, RL algorithms, and studies hyperparameter robustness and transfer to unseen agents. 4) Clear algorithmic presentation, open‐source code, and thorough ablations on RN variants add to reproducibility. 

Weaknesses: 1) Computational cost is high: SE training requires thousands of real‐environment interactions and many parallel workers, which may limit applicability to complex or high‐dimensional tasks. 2) Experiments are restricted to low‐dimensional control tasks; it remains unclear if SEs and RNs scale to pixel inputs or real‐world robotics. 3) Comparison to model‐based RL baselines is limited; the supervised dynamics model experiment suggests poor performance but merits deeper analysis. 4) Theoretical guarantees on SE convergence or RN optimality are absent. 5) Hyperparameter selection and early‐stopping heuristics add complexity.

Questions and Suggestions: Can the method handle partial observability or image‐based environments? How sensitive are results to the choice of ES hyperparameters? Would integrating meta‐gradient methods or probabilistic dynamics models reduce sample complexity? More discussion of failure modes and theoretical understanding of when SEs can mislead training would strengthen the paper.","summary_of_the_review":"The paper presents a novel performance‐driven framework for learning neural proxy environments and reward shaping functions to accelerate RL agent training. It offers strong empirical gains and transferability but suffers from high computational costs, limited domain scope, sparse comparisons to model‐based RL, and lack of theoretical analysis. Further validation on complex tasks is needed.","recommendation":"6: marginally above the acceptance threshold."}

{"summary_of_the_paper":"The paper introduces FP-DETR, a novel detection transformer that fully pre-trains the transformer encoder on ImageNet and then fine-tunes it for object detection via a lightweight task adapter. During pre-training, the authors replace the standard CNN backbone with a simple multi-scale tokenizer and remove the transformer decoder to form an encoder-only architecture. For fine-tuning, they reinterpret query positional embeddings as visual prompts and insert a self-attention–based task adapter to model inter-object relations and bridge the gap between classification and detection. Experiments on COCO, COCO-C, and Cityscapes demonstrate that FP-DETR achieves competitive mAP with fewer parameters, improved robustness to corruptions, and superior generalization on small datasets.","main_review":"Strengths: 1. Novelty: The paper tackles the challenge of pre-training the core transformer module of DETR by proposing an encoder-only pre-training strategy and a prompt-inspired task adapter. The visual prompt interpretation of query positional embeddings is conceptually appealing and well motivated. 2. Empirical performance: FP-DETR variants match or exceed the accuracy of state-of-the-art methods (DETR, Deformable DETR, UP-DETR, YOLOS) with fewer parameters, demonstrating efficiency. Robustness experiments on COCO-C and generalization on Cityscapes strengthen the claim of improved pre-training benefits. 3. Ablations: The study isolates the impact of the task adapter, comparing self-attention vs. Bi-LSTM and shared vs. per-layer adapters, validating design choices.

Weaknesses and Questions: 1. Marginal gains at the base scale: FP-DETR-Base achieves 43.3 vs. 43.8 AP for Deformable DETR on COCO; the gain is clearer in robustness but less so on clean benchmarks. 2. Pre-training cost and convergence: The added pre-training stage’s compute overhead and sensitivity to pre-training hyperparameters are not fully detailed. 3. Decoder removal: How would retaining and pre-training a decoder conditioned on multiple class tokens affect performance? 4. Ablation of prompt length or number of query embeddings could clarify prompt capacity. 5. Reproducibility: Full training and fine-tuning schedules, especially for ImageNet-21k, should be included for clarity.

Overall, the paper presents a compelling direction for leveraging full transformer pre-training in detection and offers solid empirical evidence. Addressing the points above would further strengthen the work.","summary_of_the_review":"The paper presents FP-DETR, an encoder-only pre-training strategy and a visual-prompt task adapter for detection transformers. Experiments show competitive AP, improved robustness, and generalization, with thorough ablations on the task adapter. Clarifications on marginal gains at base scale, pre-training overhead, and additional prompt ablations are recommended.","recommendation":"8: accept, good submission"}

{"summary_of_the_paper":"This paper introduces HyperDQN, a randomized exploration method for deep reinforcement learning that extends randomized least-squares value iteration (RLSVI) to the deep setting. HyperDQN uses a hypermodel to generate approximate posterior samples of the base network’s final-layer parameters via a learned mapping from a Gaussian index z, while jointly learning a nonlinear feature extractor. The training objective integrates a randomized TD loss with additive Gaussian noise and regularization to train both the hypermodel and feature network. The authors prove that, in the linear case, the optimized hypermodel recovers the posterior mean and covariance of Bayesian linear regression. Empirically, HyperDQN with 20 million frames outperforms DQN with 200 million frames on median human-normalized Atari scores, surpasses several exploration bonus and randomized methods on SuperMarioBros, and solves the deep-sea testbed more efficiently than BootDQN.","main_review":"Strengths: 1) Novel integration of a hypermodel into the last layer of a DQN-style network to capture posterior uncertainty, retaining RLSVI’s theoretical spirit. 2) A clear linear-regression analysis (Theorem 1) showing the hypermodel can recover posterior statistics. 3) Broad empirical evaluation on Atari, Mario, and deep sea demonstrating large data-efficiency gains. 4) Careful architectural choices and discussion of optimization challenges. 5) Clear comparisons to bootstrapped DQN, NoisyNet, and bonus-based methods.

Weaknesses: 1) Theoretical guarantees are limited to the linear case; no analysis under non-linear feature learning. 2) Compute and wall-clock cost of the hypermodel versus ensemble baselines is not reported. 3) Ablations on hypermodel capacity (MLP vs. linear) and on key hyperparameters (prior scale) are brief and leave open questions about sensitivity. 4) Performance is measured via maximum scores rather than mean or interquartile range, potentially overstating gains. 5) HyperDQN fails on extremely sparse tasks like Montezuma’s Revenge, and requires careful tuning of noise and regularization. 6) Combining ϵ-greedy with other methods is discouraged but remains necessary in many baselines; a more systematic study might help.

Overall, HyperDQN presents a promising direction for randomized exploration, but the paper would benefit from more thorough ablations, compute-efficiency analysis, and deeper theoretical insight into the nonlinear setting.","summary_of_the_review":"HyperDQN proposes a practical hypermodel-based posterior sampling method with a strong linear theoretical guarantee and impressive empirical improvements. However, theoretical support beyond the linear case is lacking, compute costs are unquantified, and key ablations are limited. Sparse environments remain challenging.","recommendation":"6: marginally above the acceptance threshold."}

{"summary_of_the_paper":"This paper introduces HyperDQN, a practical exploration algorithm for deep reinforcement learning that extends randomized least-squares value iteration (RLSVI). HyperDQN combines a non-linear base model for Q-value prediction with a probabilistic hypermodel that generates approximate posterior samples of the base model parameters by taking random inputs z. Joint training under a specialized TD objective enables end-to-end feature learning, efficient approximate posterior sampling without recomputing large feature covariances, and retention of RLSVI’s randomized exploration benefits. The authors prove that in the linear setting the hypermodel recovers the true posterior in expectation, and empirically demonstrate that HyperDQN outperforms DQN (20M vs 200M frames), exploration bonus methods, Bootstrapped DQN, and NoisyNet on Atari, SuperMarioBros, and the deep sea benchmark.","main_review":"Strengths: The paper tackles the critical challenge of efficient exploration in deep RL by adapting Bayesian posterior sampling to nonlinear function approximation, preserving RLSVI’s theoretical spirit while addressing its feature learning and computational limitations. The proposed hypermodel-based layer is conceptually elegant and the linear-case guarantee is clear. Experiments show sample-efficient gains on Atari, SuperMarioBros, and deep sea. The architecture and objective are well motivated, and the ablation of ϵ-greedy commitment is insightful.

Weaknesses: The theoretical analysis is limited to linear regression and does not carry over to high-dimensional nonlinear networks. The reliance on a bespoke noise term z⊤ξ and its robustness under different distributions requires deeper justification. Experimental comparisons sometimes mix training budgets (DQN at 200M vs HyperDQN at 20M), and statistical significance across seeds is not fully reported. Key design choices—hypermodel depth, number of samples, noise scale, prior weight—need more systematic ablation. Failure cases, such as Montezuma’s Revenge, are acknowledged but not deeply analyzed. Runtime and computational overhead of the hypermodel layer versus ensembles are not quantified. Clarity could be improved by consolidating methodological details and simplifying notation.

Suggestions: 1) Extend or empirically validate the linear-case guarantee in the deep network regime. 2) Provide thorough ablations on hypermodel architecture, sample count, and noise scale. 3) Report confidence intervals and average performance across seeds. 4) Compare wall-clock training time and overhead against BootDQN. 5) Analyze failure modes on extremely sparse tasks and discuss remedies. 6) Clarify exposition in Sections 4 and 5 to improve readability.","summary_of_the_review":"HyperDQN presents a promising hypermodel approach for randomized exploration in deep RL, supported by a linear-case posterior guarantee and sample-efficient gains on benchmarks. However, its theoretical scope is limited, key design choices need systematic ablation, statistical reporting is incomplete, and computational overhead is unquantified. Further empirical and theoretical validation is required.","recommendation":"6: marginally above the acceptance threshold."}

{"summary_of_the_paper":"The manuscript introduces the novel task of audio-visual dereverberation and proposes VIDA, an end-to-end model combining a Visual Acoustics Network (VAN) and a UNet-based dereverberation module with a reverb-visual matching loss. The authors construct a large-scale synthetic dataset by rendering reverberant speech in 82 Matterport3D scans using SoundSpaces, coupled with real-world recordings to demonstrate sim2real transfer. VIDA outperforms audio-only baselines and state-of-the-art speech enhancement models on speech enhancement (PESQ), automatic speech recognition (WER), and speaker verification (EER). Extensive ablations show the value of visual cues, matching loss, and human mesh input.","main_review":"Strengths: The paper tackles a compelling real-world problem by leveraging visual scene information to guide speech dereverberation, a direction unexplored by prior work. The proposed VIDA architecture is well motivated, integrating separate ResNet encoders for RGB and depth, a matching loss to align audio and visual embeddings, and a UNet for spectrogram reconstruction. The synthetic dataset—built with realistic acoustic renderings on real 3D scans—is a valuable resource, and the authors provide thorough quantitative evaluations on three downstream tasks, showing statistically significant gains. Ablations confirm the contributions of panorama views, matching loss, and speaker mesh cues. The sim2real experiments demonstrate promise for real applications. 

Weaknesses: The real-world evaluation is limited to 200 recordings and may not capture broad environmental variability; further validation on larger, more diverse real datasets is needed. The method uses single static images (panoramas or narrow FoV) and does not leverage temporal visual context, which could be important in dynamic scenes. The matching loss hyperparameters and model selection criteria require more detailed justification. Comparison to classical multi-mic dereverberation methods or explicit room parameter estimation baselines would strengthen the evaluation. The model’s runtime and computational cost on longer audio/video streams merits discussion. 

Overall, the paper presents a promising multimodal dereverberation approach with strong empirical support, but broader real-world validation and temporal modelling could further enhance its impact.","summary_of_the_review":"The review applauds the novel audio-visual dereverberation task, the well-designed VIDA architecture, and the comprehensive synthetic dataset and evaluations. It notes limited real-world validation, lack of temporal context, and the need for broader baseline comparisons and cost analysis.","recommendation":"8: accept, good submission"}

{"summary_of_the_paper":"This paper analyzes approximate dictionary learning via algorithm unrolling and compares it to classical alternating minimization (AM). The authors provide a bi‐level optimization framework for Lasso‐based dictionary learning, derive convergence rates for gradient estimates obtained by AM and by deep dictionary learning (DDL) through backpropagation, and identify numerical instabilities when unrolling too many iterations. They propose practical guidelines—favoring a small number of layers or truncated backpropagation—and introduce a stochastic line‐search procedure to scale DDL to large data sets. Experiments on synthetic Gaussian dictionaries, image denoising, and magnetoencephalography (MEG) pattern learning demonstrate faster convergence and comparable pattern recovery against state‐of‐the‐art methods.","main_review":"Strengths: The paper offers a thorough theoretical treatment of unrolled dictionary learning, including explicit bounds on gradient and Jacobian estimation errors and a clear characterization of instability regimes. The unified comparison of AM and DDL clarifies when unrolling yields benefits. The proposed stochastic line‐search SGD addresses large‐scale learning, and the MEG application showcases real‐world potential. All proofs and experimental details are provided, supporting reproducibility.

Weaknesses: The theoretical results depend on strong assumptions (support identifiability, invertibility on the support), and the constants in the error bounds are unspecified, limiting practical guidance. Empirical evaluation focuses on pattern‐recovery metrics (correlation scores) but does not assess end‐to‐end task performance (e.g., signal classification or detection accuracy). Comparisons to established baselines such as Online DL and convolutional K-SVD are present but not extensive, and sensitivity analyses over hyperparameters (λ, unroll depth) are limited. The stochastic line-search heuristic is described briefly, and its parameter tuning and convergence guarantees warrant deeper discussion.

Questions and suggestions: How sensitive are results to the choice of λ and to noise level? Can the authors report downstream task metrics (e.g., event detection rates in MEG) to quantify practical gains? An ablation study on truncated vs full backprop over varied depths would strengthen claims. It would also help to include a comparison of memory and runtime trade-offs across methods under realistic budgets. Finally, discussing scenarios where unrolling fails (e.g., very high sparsity or large λ) would provide a balanced view.","summary_of_the_review":"The paper delivers a rigorous theoretical analysis of unrolled dictionary learning and identifies when it outperforms or becomes unstable, and proposes a scalable stochastic optimizer. However, it relies on strong assumptions, provides limited empirical validation beyond pattern‐recovery correlations, and lacks broader task evaluations and sensitivity studies under varied conditions.","recommendation":"5: marginally below the acceptance threshold."}

{"summary_of_the_paper":"This paper introduces a distributionally robust, fairness‐aware variant of principal component analysis (PCA). The authors formulate a min–max optimization problem that balances total reconstruction error against subgroup error disparity, where the inner maximization is taken over all distributions within a moment‐based Wasserstein‐type ambiguity set. They reformulate the infinite‐dimensional robust fair PCA problem as a finite‐dimensional minimax program over the Stiefel manifold, derive explicit expressions, and propose a Riemannian subgradient descent algorithm with provable sublinear convergence. Empirical evaluations on several real‐world datasets demonstrate improved trade‐offs between reconstruction accuracy and fairness compared to state‐of‐the‐art baselines.","main_review":"Strengths: 1) Novel integration of distributional robustness with subgroup fairness in an unsupervised setting. 2) Rigorous reformulation of the robust fair PCA into a tractable Stiefel‐manifold minimax problem. 3) Clear derivation of explicit objective terms and algorithmic details. 4) Provable sublinear convergence for the proposed Riemannian subgradient descent. 5) Extensive empirical validation across numerous datasets showing Pareto improvements over FairPCA and CFPCA baselines. 6) Discussion of extension to nonbinary sensitive attributes.

Weaknesses and Suggestions: 1) The choice and tuning of ambiguity radii εₐ and penalty λ are critical; more guidance or automatic selection strategies (e.g., cross‐validation heuristics) could strengthen practical applicability. 2) Computational complexity and runtime comparisons with semidefinite‐programming‐based methods are not reported; please include wall‐clock times and scalability analysis. 3) Assumptions in Theorem 3.2 (eigenvalue and marginal probability bounds) should be examined empirically to assess how often they hold in practice. 4) Clarify sensitivity to manifold retraction choice and step‐size; ablation studies would be valuable. 5) Discuss limitations: out‐of‐sample fairness generalization under stronger distribution shifts and potential extension to nonlinear embeddings.

Questions for Authors: How does the method perform when the sensitive attribute has more than two categories? Can the algorithm handle very high dimensions efficiently without dimension reduction?","summary_of_the_review":"The manuscript presents a well‐motivated distributionally robust fair PCA with solid theoretical reformulation and convergence guarantees, supported by extensive experiments. Key strengths include novelty, sound derivations, and empirical Pareto gains. Areas for improvement are hyperparameter selection guidance, runtime scalability, assumption validation, and sensitivity analyses.","recommendation":"8: accept, good submission"}

{"summary_of_the_paper":"The manuscript presents ZeroFL, a framework for federated learning (FL) that leverages high‐sparsity training and local uplink sparsification to accelerate on‐device training and reduce communication. The authors first analyze the impact of applying SWAT, a centralised sparse training method, directly in FL. They identify that high sparsity levels degrade global accuracy due to diluted model updates across heterogeneous clients. They then propose three local sparsification strategies—Top-K-Weights, Diff on Top-K-Weights, and Top-K-Weights Diff—that prune or compress client updates before aggregation, controlled by a mask ratio parameter. ZeroFL is evaluated on CIFAR-10, FEMNIST, and SpeechCommands under IID and non-IID partitions. Experiments show that with 90–95% sparsity, ZeroFL achieves up to 2.3% improved accuracy over sparse FL baselines while reducing uplink communication by up to 7×. The paper contributes: (1) the first study of sparse training during FL, (2) a detailed analysis of sparsity effects, and (3) ZeroFL’s local sparsification techniques.","main_review":"Strengths: The paper addresses an important bottleneck in FL by focusing on on-device training cost rather than communication alone. The analysis of sparsity overlap and stability of active weights across rounds is insightful and well supported by empirical results. ZeroFL’s three masking strategies are simple to implement and demonstrate consistent accuracy gains at 90–95% sparsity while achieving substantial uplink compression. The experimental evaluation covers multiple datasets, non-IID partitions, and both centralised and federated baselines.

Weaknesses: The improvements in global accuracy are modest (0.4–2.3%) and sometimes inconsistent across datasets and sparsity levels. The manuscript does not report actual wall-clock speedups or energy consumption on real devices, which are critical to the stated motivation of accelerating on-device training. The evaluation is limited to small to medium-scale CNNs (ResNet-18, small FEMNIST CNN), leaving open whether ZeroFL scales to larger vision or language models. Hyperparameter sensitivity for mask ratio and learning-rate schedules is only briefly explored. Finally, comparisons to other FL optimizers (e.g. FedAvgM, FedAdam variations) are scarce.

Suggestions: Include profiling on a representative mobile CPU/GPU to validate training acceleration and energy savings. Expand evaluations to a larger model or a transformer to test generality. Compare ZeroFL against momentum-based and adaptive FL optimizers. Provide guidelines for mask-ratio selection and study its impact more systematically. Clarify storage overhead and server-side sparsity handling.","summary_of_the_review":"This paper proposes ZeroFL, a federated learning framework that uses high-sparsity training and client-side uplink masking to improve on-device training efficiency. The authors provide a solid analysis of sparsity dynamics in FL, and three simple sparsification strategies that yield modest accuracy gains and substantial communication savings. However, the work lacks real-device speedup and energy measurements, broader model evaluations, and systematic hyperparameter analysis. Overall, the concept is promising and backed by sound analysis, but additional empirical validation is needed to fully support the claims.","recommendation":"8: accept, good submission"}

{"summary_of_the_paper":"This paper addresses the challenge of estimating class-conditional feature covariances in meta-learning for improved deterministic uncertainty quantification and OOD calibration. The authors identify that empirical covariance estimation fails in few-shot settings and propose a meta-learned covariance generator based on an attentive set encoder that outputs either diagonal or diagonal-plus-low-rank factors. They further introduce an energy-based inference procedure that parameterizes a logit-normal softmax with variance scaled by the minimum energy, mitigating overconfidence from softmax shift invariance. Bi-Lipschitz regularization via spectral normalization preserves feature distances. Experiments on synthetic toy tasks, Omniglot, MiniImageNet and their corrupted variants demonstrate superior OOD calibration (ECE) while maintaining competitive in-distribution accuracy.","main_review":"Strengths: The paper identifies a clear limitation of existing covariance-based uncertainty methods in meta-learning and proposes a principled solution combining meta-learned low-rank covariance factors and energy-based softmax calibration. The use of a set transformer as a covariance encoder is well motivated by the need to capture pairwise feature interactions. The recursive inversion and determinant lemmas yield efficient inference, and bi-Lipschitz regularization ensures expressive, non-collapsed features. Extensive experiments on toy and standard few-shot benchmarks show significant ECE improvements under OOD shifts.

Weaknesses and Suggestions: 1) Baselines: Important recent meta-learning uncertainty methods such as deep kernel transfer (Patacchiola et al., 2020) are only briefly mentioned. A direct quantitative comparison would strengthen claims of novelty and performance. 2) Ablation on rank: While rank-1 and rank-2 variants are evaluated, the effect of varying the low-rank dimension and its impact on calibration vs. computation is not fully explored. 3) Clarity: The description of the logit-normal approximation and temperature tuning is dense; a clearer step-by-step derivation and pseudocode would aid reproducibility. 4) OOD evaluation: Corruptions and random novel classes are useful but limited; consider evaluating on standard OOD benchmarks (e.g., CIFAR-10 vs. SVHN) to assess generalization. 5) Implementation details: More detail on hyperparameter choices, training stability and set encoder architecture (number of blocks, heads) would help replication. 6) Computational cost: Although low-rank inference is efficient, experiments show latency increases with rank; discussing tradeoffs in practical deployments would be beneficial.

Overall, the approach is sound, original and significant for meta-learning uncertainty. Addressing the above points in revision will improve clarity and impact.","summary_of_the_review":"The paper presents a novel meta-learning framework that predicts diagonal and low-rank covariance factors via a set transformer and employs energy-based softmax calibration, yielding improved OOD calibration in few-shot settings. Experiments demonstrate strong ECE gains, though comparisons to recent baselines, detailed ablations on rank choice, clearer derivations, broader OOD tests,and more implementation detail are needed for full reproducibility and assessment.","recommendation":"8: accept, good submission"}
